data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

In .NET 10, the Cosmos DB provider deprecated synchronous query execution but still allowed it via the `CosmosOptionsExtension` sync-over-async opt-in. **In .NET 11 (EF Core 11), that opt-in is removed entirely.** Calling any synchronous LINQ operator (`ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`) or `SaveChanges()` on the Cosmos provider now throws `InvalidOperationException` at runtime — there is no configuration to re-enable it.

## The fix — convert to async

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key changes:**
1. Return `Task<T>` (or `Task` for void), mark methods `async`
2. Replace `ToList()` → `ToListAsync()`, `First()` → `FirstAsync()`, `Count()` → `CountAsync()`, `SaveChanges()` → `SaveChangesAsync()`
3. Rename methods with the `Async` suffix (convention)
4. Callers must be updated to `await` these methods — this ripples up the call chain

You can also remove the old `EnableSyncOverAsync()` / `AllowSyncOverAsync()` call from your `DbContext` configuration since it no longer compiles.
